When ["Our Origins"]

"The people of this world can be grouped into
three categories: animal folk, witches, and
non-magical humans. While there is some overlap,
our human forms are our single uniting factor.
"Animal folk are born in a wide variety of forms,
believed to be their true forms, which they are
able to return to under various conditions, and
which they MUST return to at death.
"The main identifying factor of a witch is their
ability to command magic of all sorts. Though
they are capable of transforming themselves,
their natural state is humanoid.
"Non-magical humans are classified by their
lack of inherent abilities or talents relating
to magic, as the name suggests. Like witches,
they are born and die in human form.
"The most broadly accepted theory of humankind's
origin is that witches divided into each group:
one set cursed to their strange inhuman forms,
and another set who abandoned magic entirely.
"It is also plausible to say non-magical humans
are the ones who learned magic to become witches,
giving way to an obsession with transformation,
which then led to the existence of animal folk...
"...but until we find evidence favoring either of
these theories, we can only hopelessly guess.
It remains the world's greatest mystery."


When ["Other Worlds"]

"There is no current estimate toward the number
of alternate worlds in existence, though we have
been able to travel to a small handful due to
the efforts of powerful witches.
"The most notable world we have been able to
connect to is known as the Netherworld. This realm
is inhabited by creatures called demons, and
has gone largely unexplored due to its vastness.
"We have very little information on other worlds
and their histories, but it is abundantly clear
something higher than magic has bridged the gaps
between existing worlds long before us.
"Although the worlds we know have all developed
independently, there are striking, impossible to
ignore similarities between them: specifically
the common humanoid forms, and the names of gods.
"The existence of gods is surrounded by mystery.
Most of the information gathered on the subject
is unreliable, as many legends have been passed
down through unverifiable oral tradition.
"Though gods are elusive in nature, the fact that
they are known by the same names across dimensions
is proof enough for many that they truly do exist."

Play BGM: 'lost in snow', 85, 100

Believe it or not, there was a time
this old rabbit hated wolves.
Hard to imagine, eh?
I used to live in a town near here,
with my wife and 8 children.
The youngest... why, she'd be about
your age now, Trick.
One day, out foraging with my daughter...
wouldn't you know it, the first time
I bring her along on my usual route,
we cross paths with a wolf!
I told her to run home as fast as her
little legs would carry her...
then I gave that wolf the what for!
Oughta be ashamed, scaring a child.
But not long into my lecturin'...
The mountain rumbled and roared,
and we quickly realized we'd been
caught in an avalanche!
Thank my lucky stars, I survived.
My right leg was broke though,
must've banged it against a rock. But,
I was too worked up to pay it any mind.
I burrowed my way out of the snow
pretty easy. Then, when I poked my
head out, I came face to face with
that wolf! Fangs, claws, and all!
Y'see, I'd always been told that a wolf
who's ready to kill takes its beast form.
Easier to rend its prey like that.
Seeing him just about scared me to death!
"Please don't eat me!
I have a wife and 8 children!"
I begged him.
And he blinked at me in return.
"Do you want to return to them?"
I'd never expected a question like that
to come from behind those huge fangs.
I didn't know what to say.
"If you give me somethin' to eat,
I'll carry you to the main road.
You can reach your home from there,"
he said.
So I opened up my rucksack and
handed over the only food I had.
One measly rice ball.
Surely not enough to sate a wolf.
But wouldn'tcha know it,
he took it anyway.
He lifted me right up out of the snow,
and we stumbled our way back to
the main road, just as he promised.
And when it came time to part ways...
"Why didn't you eat me back there?
If you were hungry, my meat would've
done you better than a plain old
rice ball," I said to him.
"I have a daughter too," he told me.
"When I looked at you,
I thought of that."

The air in the bathing area is warm and fragrant.
Flower petals decorate the water's surface, and
a light steam embraces the pair as they enter.
They have the whole bath to themselves.
Mochi has already gone on ahead.
She beckons for Treat to join her in the water.
The wolf hesitates, gathering her resolve,
before finally taking a step forward.
She can't act too nervous around her dear friend.
Every action is carefully measured, as to not
make Mochi feel uncomfortable.
...But Mochi has never felt uncomfortable.
Treat knows she's been overly cautious,
but there's just no getting around it.
Being honest about her feelings would change things.
It would definitely change things...
As Treat slips into the comfort of the hot springs,
she thinks...

Maybe something DOES need to change.
But that would mean making a choice.
And she can only choose one.

...Ah, but didn't she decide just now?

could mess around a little.

The air in the bathing area is warm and fragrant.
Flower petals decorate the water's surface, and
a light steam embraces the group as they enter.
They have the whole bath to themselves.
Moxie, hurrying ahead of her friends, calls out
a challenge to race to the bath. Mochi gives a
gentle reminder of the "no running" rule,
despite breaking into a small jog herself.
Treat's pace remains completely unchanged
as Moxie splashes into the water, with Mochi
not far behind.
She can't help but smile at the scene.
It was times like this that Treat felt the happiest.
Living with Mochi and getting to spend so much
time with her was wonderful.
Of course, she had been close with Moxie, too.
But nothing felt better than when they were
all able to be together.
She wanted that.
Always. More than anything.
As Treat slips into the comfort of the hot springs
with her two, dear friends...

She thinks carefully about how to proceed.

To which, she is rewarded with another kiss.

She thought it wasn't an option at all.
Wolves are bad.
And Treat is a bad wolf.
So it isn't fair for her to be able to
feel this much happiness, is it?

but those fears soon melt away.
To be held, and kissed, and touched,
by the both of them like this...

Is far too much for the wolf's lonely heart.
And things get...

REALLY carried away...

When [book 1]
Loop

"The All-in-one Book of Lore, Book 1"

Show Choices: "Our Origins", "Other Worlds", put it away
When ["Our Origins"]

"The people of this world can be grouped into
three categories: animal folk, witches, and
non-magical humans. While there is some overlap,
our human forms are our single uniting factor.
"Animal folk are born in a wide variety of forms,
believed to be their true forms, which they are
able to return to under various conditions, and
which they MUST return to at death.
"The main identifying factor of a witch is their
ability to command magic of all sorts. Though
they are capable of transforming themselves,
their natural state is humanoid.
"Non-magical humans are classified by their
lack of inherent abilities or talents relating
to magic, as the name suggests. Like witches,
they are born and die in human form.
"The most broadly accepted theory of humankind's
origin is that witches divided into each group:
one set cursed to their strange inhuman forms,
and another set who abandoned magic entirely.
"It is also plausible to say non-magical humans
are the ones who learned magic to become witches,
giving way to an obsession with transformation,
which then led to the existence of animal folk...
"...but until we find evidence favoring either of
these theories, we can only hopelessly guess.
It remains the world's greatest mystery."


When ["Other Worlds"]

"There is no current estimate toward the number
of alternate worlds in existence, though we have
been able to travel to a small handful due to
the efforts of powerful witches.
"The most notable world we have been able to
connect to is known as the Netherworld. This realm
is inhabited by creatures called demons, and
has gone largely unexplored due to its vastness.
"We have very little information on other worlds
and their histories, but it is abundantly clear
something higher than magic has bridged the gaps
between existing worlds long before us.
"Although the worlds we know have all developed
independently, there are striking, impossible to
ignore similarities between them: specifically
the common humanoid forms, and the names of gods.
"The existence of gods is surrounded by mystery.
Most of the information gathered on the subject
is unreliable, as many legends have been passed
down through unverifiable oral tradition.
"Though gods are elusive in nature, the fact that
they are known by the same names across dimensions
is proof enough for many that they truly do exist."


When [put it away]
Break Loop

Branch End
Control Switches: [0137:readbooks2] = ON

Repeat Above

When [book 2]
Loop

"The All-in-one Book of Lore, Book 2"

Show Choices: "More on Witches", "History of Animal Folk", put it away
When ["More on Witches"]

"Witches are often deceptive in nature due to
the flexibility their magic allows them.
Transformative spells are incredibly common,
as they take great stock in appearances.
"Non-magical humans are historically distrustful of
witches for their willingness to deceive others.
It is said that a disregard for integrity is the
logical consequence of being able to bend reality.
"Certain breeds of animal folk seem more drawn to
witches than others, even entering into master-
servant type relationships. In those cases, they
are referred to as familiars, or pets.
"Much like the other types of humans, witches
generally prefer the company of their own kind.
This has led to the creation of many witch towns
across the world. Quite a few are magic-exclusive.
"Every witch is born with a predetermined amount of
magic to be used throughout their lifespan, and are
said to be immortal until that magic runs out.*
*This has yet to be proven but is widely supported.
"Magic cannot be transferred except via inheritance
from parent to offspring. If a witch could find a
way around this rule, they could theoretically
use magic transfer to achieve immortality.
"For that potential alone, witches are easily
regarded as the most powerful beings native to
this world."


When ["History of Animal Folk"]

"Humankind's history is riddled with injustice
and oppression, with animal folk often receiving
a disproportionate amount of cruel and unusual
treatment from witches, humans, and each other."
"Within animal folk societies, food chains have
been known to develop in similar patterns.
Certain species are inclined to carnivorous habits,
while others remain herbivores.
"Predators often form tribes to prey on others,
seeking the delicious meat obtained from a
successful hunt. Certain meats are considered
to be irresistible depending on the species.
"The meat of many birds, fish, and mammals are
also popular with witches and non-magical humans.
Meat consumption was previously avoided due to
ethical issues, up until the recent era..."
"...when agriculture alone became unable to
sustain the world's growing population.
Despite humanity's natural aversion
to homicide, desperation won out.
"The witches created an industry out of enchanting
unborn animal folk to never develop their human
forms. This resulted in animal meat becoming
much more socially acceptable to indulge in.
"Since that turning point, food shortages have been
exceedingly rare. Through the sacrifice of select
species of animal folk, we have all been able to
continue to thrive in this world."


When [put it away]
Break Loop

Branch End
Control Switches: [0137:readbooks2] = ON

Repeat Above

When [nevermind]
Break Loop

Branch End

even spanning across dimensions!

standing in now.
